Simpson’s diversity takes into account the number of individuals (n) in each species (i) and the total number of individuals of all species (N). I will calculate the Simpson’s diversity index in each habitat and compare them.

First I will look at the number of individuals in each species in the oak1 habitat

n<-birds$Oak1
n
##  [1] 35 26 25 21 16 11  6  5  3  3  3  3  3  2  2  2  1  1  1  1  0  0  0  0  0
## [26]  0  0  0  0  0  0

And the total of n as N (in just the Oak1 habitat)

N<-sum(n)
N
## [1] 170

From that we can calculate the Simpson’s index (D) of the Oak1 habitat

D<-1-sum(n*(n-1))/(N*(N-1))
D
## [1] 0.8852767

We can write a function to do this for any vector of species.

sdiFunc<-function(x){
  N<-sum(x)
  D<-1-sum(x*(x-1)) / (N*(N-1))
  D
}

oak1Div<-sdiFunc(x=birds$Oak1)
oak1Div
## [1] 0.8852767

Then we can apply that function to all the columns (habitats) in birds

sdiHabitat<-apply(birds[,-1], MARGIN=2, FUN=sdiFunc) # don't want first column because it is the bird species names
sdiHabitat
##      Oak1      Oak2      Oak3       Yew     Sitka    Norway     Mixed    Patchy 
## 0.8852767 0.8738996 0.8347812 0.8910759 0.7780180 0.8284879 0.8996337 0.9179604 
##    Swampy 
## 0.9044444

Visualization of bird diversity by habitat

sdiHabitat <- sdiHabitat %>% as_tibble %>% add_column(Habitat = names(sdiHabitat))
ggplot(data = sdiHabitat, mapping = aes(x=value,y=reorder(Habitat,-value))) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  labs(x="Simpson's Diversity Index",y=element_blank())

We do not know if this is meaningful because we don’t have any error for this. We can get this through bootstrapping!

Bootstrapping

We will take 10,000 samples of the diversity data of Oak1 habitat, with replacement. Taking sample that is the same length as the initial sample. R= number of bootstrap replicates.

R<-1e4 #10,000 replicates
# structure to hold results
sdiDistOak1<-numeric()
for(i in 1:R){
  x<-birds$Oak1
  xSamp<-sample(x,size=length(x), replace=TRUE)
  sdiDistOak1[i]<-sdiFunc(xSamp) #sdiDistOak1 will be a vector of 10,000 diversity estimates for Oak1
}

ggplot() + geom_density(mapping=aes(x=sdiDistOak1),
                        fill="lightblue",color=NA,alpha=0.7) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = oak1Div,color="blue",linetype="dashed") +
  labs(x="Simpson's Diversity Index",y="Density")

Mean of the distribution is where our line is but we have much more information now.

mean(sdiDistOak1)
## [1] 0.8849621

Can calculate a confidence interval for the statistic using the quantile function.

ci95Oak1 <- quantile(sdiDistOak1,probs = c(0.025,0.975))
names(ci95Oak1) <- c("lower","upper")
ci95Oak1
##     lower     upper 
## 0.8221762 0.9229668

Plot with confidence interval added.

ggplot() + geom_density(mapping=aes(x=sdiDistOak1),fill="lightblue",color=NA,alpha=0.7) + 
    geom_vline(xintercept = oak1Div,color="blue",linetype="dashed") +
  geom_errorbarh(mapping=aes(xmin=ci95Oak1[1],xmax=ci95Oak1[2],y=0),
                              color="blue") +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x = oak1Div,y=0),
             color="blue",size=4) +
    labs(x="Simpson's Diversity Index",y="Density")

Do it with Boot

Instead of doing a bunch of loops, can use the boot library. A little less clear what exactly is happening but much more efficient. Can use the boot function to calculate any statistic that we want it to calculate.

Here is a function that replaces our dsiFunc with something that the boot library understands.

# this is the function boot will understand
sdiBootFunc<-function(x, indicies) { #indicies function lets the boot function know how we want the data to be shuffled
  y<-x[indicies] #shuffle along this vector, combines function we wrote above with the loop
  N<-sum(y)
  D<-1-sum(y*(y-1))/ (N*(N-1))
  D
}
# the actual bootstrapping with R replicates
sdiOakBoot<-boot(birds$Oak1, sdiBootFunc, R=1e4)
sdiOakBoot
## 
## ORDINARY NONPARAMETRIC BOOTSTRAP
## 
## 
## Call:
## boot(data = birds$Oak1, statistic = sdiBootFunc, R = 10000)
## 
## 
## Bootstrap Statistics :
##      original       bias    std. error
## t1* 0.8852767 -4.90611e-05  0.02609721

We can replicate the plot above.

ggplot() + geom_density(mapping=aes(x=sdiOakBoot$t),
                        fill="lightblue",color=NA,alpha=0.7) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = sdiOakBoot$t0,color="blue",linetype="dashed") +
  labs(x="Simpson's Diversity Index",y="Density")

Can use boot.ci function to calculate several different confidence intervals.

boot.ci(sdiOakBoot)
## Warning in boot.ci(sdiOakBoot): bootstrap variances needed for studentized
## intervals

My Work

I will attempt to use lapply() function to apply the boot function to each habitat

# Here is my bootstrap function
sdiOakBoot<-function(x){
  boot(x, sdiBootFunc, R=1e4)
}

# Here I am applying it to all of the habitats
HabitatBoot<-lapply(birds[,-1], function(x) sdiOakBoot(x))

Now I will plot these as a ridgeline plot. First I need to make it into a data frame.
